\begin_layout Section
The Uncovered Interest Parity (UIP)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are 2 alternatives to investing 1 unit of domestic currency:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Investing 1 local amount in domestic bonds yields 
\begin_inset Formula $1+i$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Investing in foreign bonds.
 Requires fist exchanging to foreign currency 
\begin_inset Formula $(\frac{1}{e}$
\end_inset

 foreign currency).
 That yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{e}(1+i^{*})$
\end_inset

 in foreign currency in the 
\series bold
next
\series default
 period, which is 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{e^{E}}{e}(1+i^{*})$
\end_inset

 in domestic currency
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In an equilibrium both returns are equal:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+i=(1+i^{*})\frac{e^{E}}{e}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the former is higher - instead of investing in the local currency, the
 best thing to do would be to get a loan from a foreign bank and invest
 it domestically.
 This arbitrage requires 2 things to happen - loan availability and correct
 assumption regarding the future exchange rate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Example: Eliezer Fischman - increase of interest in Turkish Lira.
 He exchange shekels to Lira, bought (high-yield) bonds, but then the Lira
 had depreciated and he had to default.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hedging could have been achieved by some sort of a future contract.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-arbitrage condition can be simplified to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+i=(1+i^{*})\left(1+\frac{e^{E}}{e}-1\right)=(1+i^{*})\left(1+\frac{e^{E}-e}{e}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\frac{e^{E}-e}{e}$
\end_inset

 is the 
\series bold
expected depreciation
\series default
.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1+i\cong1+i^{*}+\frac{e^{E}-e}{e}
\]

\end_inset

neglecting the cross-term, because it is very small
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interpretation is: 
\series bold
the domestic interest rate has to equal the world interest rate, plus expected
 depreciation
\series default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus the local interest rate equals the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

world interest rate
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, with compensation for depreciation (otherwise, no one will be willing
 to buy domestic bonds).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Given values of 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{E}$
\end_inset

, if interest rate (
\begin_inset Formula $i)$
\end_inset

 is high, the exchange rate (
\begin_inset Formula $e)$
\end_inset

 must be low, and vice-versa.
 If current exchange rate equals to the future (expected) exchange rate),
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $i=i^{*}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $e=e^{E}$
\end_inset

 (the world interest rate equals to the domestic interest rate).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Countries with a weak currency will usually have high interest rate, and
 vice-versa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If there is a change in the exogenous variables, the curve will shift.
 For example, an increase in world interest rate will shift the curve to
 the right.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When the interest rates stays the same, if 
\begin_inset Formula $i^{*}$
\end_inset

 increases, 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 must increase as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
