\begin_layout Section
The Trilemma
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There is a tradeoff between fixed exchange rate, independent monetary policy
 and fre capital flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Each country might (want to) have each of these 3 policies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Free capital flow
\series default
 is beneficial, as it allows free trade & investment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
independent monetary policy 
\series default
means the ability to decide locally on an interest rate and not be forced
 by some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

world
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 entity which is beneficial as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Fixed exchange rate
\series default
 is also beneficial, as it allow planning ahead of future investmens (not
 being afraid that debt would have to be repaid with higher amount of currency).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trilemma is that it is not possible to have all 3 things, but one of
 them had to be given up.
\end_layout

